WEBVTT

00:04.132 --> 00:05.253
Okay. One of the most educational lessons that I 
believe that I ever observed in my life on the ranch

00:05.273 --> 00:16.388
was down on Pepper Bluff. There's only one passage 
up that bluff that you could get over it and get to

00:17.409 --> 00:24.539
the Three Springs Passage. Horseback. And you had 
to go around the point of the bluff, and if you

00:27.202 --> 00:32.569
didn't have a sure-footed horse, you're... just 
as sure to get dunked in that hole of water, which

00:33.106 --> 00:42.908
was about 10 to 20 feet deep as you were for, dime was 
for a ginger snapper. Now that was regular, but

00:43.409 --> 00:47.899
that was the only way we could get there. And we'd go 
up this bluff and go to Three Springs Pasture to

00:52.057 --> 00:55.644
gather the cattle to bring back. We didn't bring 
them back that way. We'd have to take them a mile and

00:57.929 --> 01:03.199
a half to two miles up the river to cross them. Now 
that was real work. And you knew what you had to do,

01:05.925 --> 01:10.013
and you didn't ask questions. But we came around 
the point of Pepper Bluff, which Definitely the

01:14.078 --> 01:27.492
water comes right up to the bluff itself, and you 
bring your horse right down at the edge of it, and

01:14.078 --> 01:27.492
the rock slants into the water, and it's slick as 
owl's grease. And if you're not very careful, and

01:28.393 --> 01:36.182
you must give your horse its own time. Don't kick 
him. Don't spur him. Let him feel his way and let him

01:39.712 --> 01:44.418
be a sure-footed person. He's got more sense about 
that than you have. Right. So let him go. And we got

01:49.685 --> 02:05.726
around this point, and I saw an old mama coon, and I 
hollered at my daddy, and he took his finger up to my

01:49.685 --> 02:05.726
mouth and he shook it to be quiet. Mm-hmm. And I went 
on over to where he was. He said, I want to show you

02:09.246 --> 02:11.831
something. All right, she came up this trail, and 
she had four babies behind her. Oh, yeah. And she

02:17.702 --> 02:19.605
got up to this pond. I said pond. She got up to this 
hole of water. Mm-hmm. And just before you get to

02:23.907 --> 02:39.220
this real deep hole, there was an eddy water hole 
out at the side, which was about, oh, I guess maybe

02:23.907 --> 02:39.220
12 inches deep. But you could see the fish running 
in it, and you could see lots of minnows, great big

02:39.240 --> 02:46.527
red-hossed minnows. And we were way back, not way 
back, but we were... I guess we were about 25 or 30

02:52.831 --> 03:02.891
feet back and there was a big rock in front of us. So 
we put our horses there and my daddy told me to get on

03:02.931 --> 03:11.188
top of this rock so I could watch all the 
maneuvering. So the old mama coon raccoon yeah but

03:13.216 --> 03:36.034
we call them coons out here comes up this trail and 
she gets to this hole this eddy water and she takes

03:13.216 --> 03:36.034
number one and sets him and she just takes him with 
both hands with her front feet and just socks him

